00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,732
CHAPTER XLII.

2
00:00:00,792 --> 00:00:02,695
THE WHITENESS OF THE WHALE.

3
00:00:03,676 --> 00:00:10,144
What the white whale was to Ahab has been hinted what, at times, he was to me, as yet remains unsaid.

4
00:00:10,305 --> 00:00:29,430
Aside from those more obvious considerations touching Moby Dick, which could not but occasionally awaken in any man's soul some alarm, there was another thought, or rather vague, nameless horror concerning him, which at times, by its intensity, completely overpowered all the rest.

5
00:00:29,410 --> 00:00:37,680
And yet so mystical and well-nigh ineffable was it, that I almost despair of putting it in a comprehensible form.

6
00:00:37,901 --> 00:00:41,025
It was the whiteness of the whale that above all things appalled me.

7
00:00:41,806 --> 00:00:44,048
But how can I hope to explain myself here?

8
00:00:44,990 --> 00:00:50,136
And yet, in some ding, random way, explain myself I must.

9
00:00:50,116 --> 00:00:52,419
else all these chapters might be naught.

10
00:00:52,879 --> 00:01:15,145
Though in many natural objects whiteness refiningly enhances beauty, as if imparting some special virtue of its own, as in marbles, japonicas, and pearls, and though various nations have in some way recognized a certain royal preeminence in this hue, even the barbaric grand old kings of Pegu placing the title Lord of the White Elephants, above all their other magniliquent ascriptions of dominions,

11
00:01:15,125 --> 00:01:37,639
and the modern kings of Siam unfurling the same snow-white quadruped in the royal standard, in the royal standard, and the Hanoverian flag bearing theâ€”this elusive quality it is, which causes the thought of whiteness, when divorced from more kindly associations, and coupled with any object terrible in itself, to heighten that terror to the furthest bounds.

12
00:01:37,619 --> 00:01:41,563
Witness the white bear of the poles, And the white shark of the tropics.

13
00:01:42,584 --> 00:02:07,508
What but their smooth, flaky whiteness Makes them the transcendent horrors they are, That ghastly whiteness it is which imparts Such an abhorrent mildness, even more loathsome Than terrific, to the dumb gloating of their aspect, So that not the fierce-fanged tiger in his heraldic coat Can so stagger courage as the white-shrouded bear or shark

14
00:02:07,488 --> 00:02:32,719
Keir referenced to the polar bear, it may possibly be urged by him who would fain go still deeper into this matter, that it is not the whiteness, separately regarded, which heightens the intolerable hideousness of that brute foreanalyzed, that heightened hideousness, it might be said, only rises from the circumstance that the irresponsible ferociousness of the creature stands invested in the fleece of celestial innocence and love,

15
00:02:32,699 --> 00:02:37,424
and non-heed by bringing together two such opposite emotions in our minds, the polar bear.

16
00:02:37,464 --> 00:02:45,853
But even assuming all this to be true, yet, were it not for the whiteness, you would not have that intensified terror.

17
00:02:46,133 --> 00:02:57,846
As for the white shark, the white gliding ghostliness of repose in that creature, when beheld in his ordinary moods, strangely tallies with the same quality in the polar quadruped.

18
00:02:59,227 --> 00:03:04,840
This peculiarity is most vividly hit by the French in the name they bestow upon that fish.

19
00:03:05,362 --> 00:03:15,987
The Romish Mass for the dead begins with Requiem, Aeternam minus Aeternal Rest, whence our Requiem denominating the Mass itself, and any other funeral music.

20
00:03:15,967 --> 00:03:25,468
Now, in allusion to the white, silent stillness of death in this shark, and the mild deadliness of his habits, the French call him Rayquine.

21
00:03:25,689 --> 00:03:27,292
Bethink thee of the albatross!

22
00:03:27,834 --> 00:03:35,190
Whence come those clouds of spiritual wonderment and pale dread, in which that white phantom sails in all imaginations?

23
00:03:35,170 --> 00:03:42,040
Not Coleridge first threw that spell, but God's great, unflattering laureate, Nature.

24
00:03:42,761 --> 00:03:46,427
Cur, I remember the first albatross I ever saw.

25
00:03:46,467 --> 00:03:53,297
It was during a prolonged gale, in waters hard upon the Antarctic seas, from my Fornian watch below.

26
00:03:53,277 --> 00:04:05,157
I ascended to the overclouded deck, and there, dashed upon the main hatches, I saw a regal, feathery thing of unspotted whiteness, and with a hoped Roman bill sublime.

27
00:04:05,237 --> 00:04:12,028
At intervals it arched forth its vast archangel wings, as if to embrace some holy ark.

28
00:04:12,008 --> 00:04:14,290
Wondrous flutterings and throbbings shook it.

29
00:04:15,191 --> 00:04:23,400
Though bodily unharmed, it uttered cries, as some king's ghost in supernatural distress, through its inexpressible strange eyes.

30
00:04:24,081 --> 00:04:27,525
Methought I peeped to secrets which took cold of God.

31
00:04:27,725 --> 00:04:41,560
As Abraham before the angels, I bowed myself the white thing was so white, its wings so wide, and in those forever exiled waters, I had lost the miserable warping memories of traditions and of towns.

32
00:04:42,181 --> 00:04:44,744
Long I gazed at that prodigy of plumage.

33
00:04:44,985 --> 00:04:49,170
I cannot tell, can only hint, the things that datter through me then.

34
00:04:50,192 --> 00:04:54,738
But at last I awoke in turning, asked a sailor what bird was this.

35
00:04:55,719 --> 00:04:57,141
A gunny, he replied.

36
00:04:57,942 --> 00:04:58,302
Gunny!

37
00:04:58,783 --> 00:05:00,345
Never had heard that name before.

38
00:05:00,806 --> 00:05:04,691
Is it conceivable that this gory thing is utterly unknown to men ashore?

39
00:05:04,871 --> 00:05:05,212
Never.

40
00:05:06,213 --> 00:05:11,580
But some time after I learned that Gunny was some seaman's name for Albatross.

41
00:05:12,404 --> 00:05:22,426
so that by no possibility could Coleridge's wild rhyme have had aught to do with those mystical impressions which were mine, when I saw that bird upon our deck.

42
00:05:22,446 --> 00:05:27,797
For neither had I then read the rhyme, nor knew the bird to be an albatross.

43
00:05:27,777 --> 00:05:35,666
Yet, in saying this, I do but indirectly burnish a little brighter the noble merit of the poem and the poet.

44
00:05:35,686 --> 00:05:56,890
I assert, then, that in the wondrous bodily whiteness of the bird chiefly lurks the secret of the spell, and truth the more evinced in this, that by a solacism of terms there are birds called grey albatrosses, and these I have frequently seen, but never with such emotions as when I beheld the Antarctic fowl.

45
00:05:56,870 --> 00:05:59,635
But how had the mystic thing been caught?

46
00:06:00,776 --> 00:06:06,947
Whisper it not, and I will tell With a treacherous hook and line, As the fowl floated on the sea.

47
00:06:07,347 --> 00:06:18,005
At last the captain made a postman Of it, tying a lettered leathern tally Round its neck, with the ship's time and place, And then letting it escape.

48
00:06:18,105 --> 00:06:23,434
But I doubt not That leathern tally meant for man Was taken off in heaven.

49
00:06:23,414 --> 00:06:29,508
when the white fowl flew to join the wing-folding, the invoking, and adoring cherubim.

50
00:06:29,689 --> 00:06:39,432
Most famous in our Western annuals and Indian traditions is that of the white steed of the prairies, a magnificent milk-white charger.

51
00:06:39,412 --> 00:06:47,882
large-eyed, small-headed, glove-chested, and with the dignity of a thousand monarchs in his lofty, overscorning carriage.

52
00:06:47,902 --> 00:06:57,332
He was the elected Xerxes of vast herds of wild horses, whose pastures in those days were only fenced by the rocky mountains and the Alleghenies.

53
00:06:58,253 --> 00:07:06,162
At their flaming head he westward trooped it like that chosen star which every evening leads on the hosts of life.

54
00:07:06,142 --> 00:07:17,433
The flashing cascade of his mane, the curving comet of his tail, invested him with housings more resplendent than gold and silver beaters could have furnished him.

55
00:07:17,994 --> 00:07:32,368
A most imperial and archangelical apparition of that unfallen western world, which to the eyes of the old trappers and hunters revived the glories of those primeval times when Adam walked majestic as a god,

56
00:07:32,348 --> 00:07:49,547
bluff-browed and fearless as this mighty steed, whether marching amid his aides and marshals in the van of countless cohorts that endlessly streamed it over the plains, like in Ohio, whether with his circumambient subjects browsing all around at the horizon,

57
00:07:49,527 --> 00:07:55,961
The white steed gallopingly reviewed them with warm nostrils reddening through his cool milkiness.

58
00:07:56,663 --> 00:08:05,663
Sin, whatever aspect he presented himself, always to the bravest Indians he was the object of trembling reverence and awe.

59
00:08:05,643 --> 00:08:27,533
Nor can it be questioned, from what stands on legendary record of this noble horse, that it was his spiritual whiteness chiefly which so clothed him with divineness, and that this divineness had that in it which, though commanding worship, at the same time enforced a certain nameless terror.

60
00:08:27,513 --> 00:08:36,683
There are other instances where this whiteness loses all that accessory and strange glory which invests it in the white steed and albatross.

61
00:08:37,183 --> 00:08:46,734
What is it that in the albino man so peculiarly repels and often shocks the eye, as that sometimes he is loathed by his own kith and kin?

62
00:08:47,755 --> 00:08:52,440
It is that whiteness which invests him, a thing expressed by the name he bears.

63
00:08:52,657 --> 00:09:04,219
The albino is as well made as other men has no substantive deformity, and yet this mere aspect of all-pervading whiteness makes him more strangely hideous than the ugliest abortion.

64
00:09:05,954 --> 00:09:07,155
Why should this be so?

65
00:09:07,356 --> 00:09:19,048
Nor, in quite other aspects, does nature in her least palpable but not the less malicious agencies fail to enlist among her forces this crowning attribute of the terrible.

66
00:09:20,029 --> 00:09:26,617
From its snowy aspect the gauntleted ghost of the southern seas has been denominated the White Squall.

67
00:09:27,297 --> 00:09:29,700
Nor, in some historic instances,

68
00:09:29,680 --> 00:09:33,669
Has the art of human malice omitted so potent an auxiliary?

69
00:09:33,790 --> 00:09:47,301
How wildly it heightens the effect of that passage in Foissat, when, masked in the snowy symbol of their faction, the desperate white hoods of Ghent murder their bailiff in the marketplace.

70
00:09:47,281 --> 00:09:56,814
Nor, in some things, does the common, hereditary experience of all mankind fail to bear witness to the supernaturalism of this hue.

71
00:09:57,034 --> 00:10:15,820
It cannot well be doubted that the one visible quality in the aspect of the dead which most appalls the gazer is the marble pallor lingering there, as if, indeed, that pallor were as much like the badge of consternation in the other world as of mortal trepidation here.

72
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:22,730
And from that pallor of the dead we borrow the expressive hue of the shroud in which we wrap them.

73
00:10:22,850 --> 00:10:31,682
Nor even in our superstitions do we fail to throw the same snowy mantle round our phantoms, all ghosts rising in a milk-white fogier.

74
00:10:32,383 --> 00:10:41,976
While these terrors seize us, let us add, that even the king of terrors, when personified by the evangelist, rides on his pallid horse.

75
00:10:41,956 --> 00:10:48,584
Therefore, in his other moods, symbolize whatever grand or gracious thing he will by whiteness.

76
00:10:49,124 --> 00:10:56,793
No man can deny that in its profoundest idealized significance it calls up a peculiar apparition to the soul.

77
00:10:56,913 --> 00:11:02,460
But though without dissent this point be fixed, how is mortal man to account for it?

78
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:05,483
To analyze it would seem impossible.

79
00:11:05,463 --> 00:11:27,960
Can we, then, by the citation of some of those instances wherein this thing of whiteness, though, for the time either wholly or in great part stripped of all direct associations, calculated to impart to it, ought fearful, but nevertheless is found to exert over us the same sorcery, however modified, consons?

80
00:11:27,940 --> 00:11:33,025
thus hope to light upon some chance clue to conduct us to the hidden cause we seek.

81
00:11:33,165 --> 00:11:33,866
Let us try.

82
00:11:33,906 --> 00:11:42,514
But in a matter like this, subtlety appeals to subtlety, and without imagination no man can follow another into these halls.

83
00:11:42,794 --> 00:11:56,867
And though, doubtless, some at least of the imaginative impressions about to be presented may have been shared by most men, yet few, perhaps, were entirely conscious of them at the time.

84
00:11:56,847 --> 00:11:59,651
and therefore may not be able to recall them now.

85
00:11:59,791 --> 00:12:19,598
Why, to the man of untutored ideality, who happens to be but loosely acquainted with the peculiar character of the day, does the bare mention of Whitsuntide Marshall in the fancy such long, dreary, speechless processions of slow-pacing pilgrims, downcast and hooded with new-fallen snow?

86
00:12:19,662 --> 00:12:32,641
or, to the unread, unsophisticated Protestants of the Middle American States, why does the passing mention of a white friar or a white nun evoke such an eyeless statue in the soul?

87
00:12:32,802 --> 00:12:37,789
Or what is there, apart from the traditions of dungeoned warriors and kings,

88
00:12:37,769 --> 00:12:54,900
will not wholly account for it that makes the White Tower of London tell so much more strongly on the imagination of an untravelled American than those other storied structures, its neighbours, the Byward Tower, or even the Bloody.

89
00:12:54,880 --> 00:13:13,733
And those sublimer towers, the white mountains of New Hampshire, whence, in peculiar moods, comes that gigantic ghostliness over the soul at the bare mention of that name, while the thought of Virginia's Blue Ridge is full of a soft, dewy, distant dreaminess,

90
00:13:13,713 --> 00:13:34,118
Or why, irrespective of all latitudes and longitudes, does the name of the White Sea exert such a spectralness over the fancy, while that of the Yellow Sea lulls us with mortal thoughts of long, lacquered, mild afternoons on the waves, followed by the gaudiest and yet sleepiest of sunsets?

91
00:13:34,486 --> 00:13:58,283
Or, to choose a wholly unsubstantial instance, purely addressed to the fancy, why, in reading the old fairy tales of Central Europe, does the tall, pale man of the Harz forests, whose changeless pallor unrustingly glides through the green of the groves, why, is this phantom more terrible than all the whooping imps of the Broxburghs?

92
00:13:58,263 --> 00:14:16,710
nor is it, altogether, the remembrance of her cathedral-toppling earthquakes, nor the stampedos of her frantic seas, nor the tearlessness of arid skies that never rain, nor the sight of her wide field of leaning spires, wrenched copestones, and crosses all adroop, like canted yards of anchored fleets low.

93
00:14:16,690 --> 00:14:22,463
and her suburban avenues of house-walls lying over upon each other, as a tossed pack of cards.

94
00:14:23,004 --> 00:14:34,530
It is not these things alone which make tearless Lima the strangest, saddest city, though, for Lima has taken the white veil, and there is a higher horror in this whiteness of her woe.

95
00:14:34,949 --> 00:14:49,406
Old as Pizarro, this whiteness keeps her ruins forever new, admits not the cheerful greenness of complete decay, spreads over her broken ramparts the rigid pallor of an apoplexy that fixes its own distortions.

96
00:14:50,226 --> 00:15:01,159
I know that, to the common apprehension, this phenomenon of whiteness is not confessed to be the prime agent in exaggerating the terror of objects otherwise terrible.

97
00:15:01,139 --> 00:15:18,085
Nor, to the unimaginative mind, is there aught of terror in those appearances whose awfulness to another mind almost solely consists in this one phenomenon, especially when exhibited under any form at all approaching to muteness or universality.

98
00:15:18,672 --> 00:15:25,700
What I mean by these two statements may, perhaps, be respectively elucidated by the following examples.

99
00:15:26,021 --> 00:15:39,617
First whole, the mariner, when drawing nigh the coasts of foreign lands, if by night he hear the roar of breakers, starts to vigilance, and feels just enough of trepidation to sharpen all his faculties, but under precisely similar circumstances

100
00:15:39,597 --> 00:15:49,156
